# Debug Logs

```java
List<String> accounts = [SELECT Id FROM Account];
```


Salesforce explains debug log in a very accurate way:

_The debug log contains information about each transaction, such as whether it was successful and how long it took. Depending on the filters set by your trace flags, the log can contain varying levels of detail about the transaction. ~ Salesforce_

In short: 
- Debug logs contains wide information about each transaction.
- Depending on the filters you've selected those information are less or more detailed.

Debug logs are the most common and widely used technique. Probably, because it's also the easiest one, but equally powerful as others. With debug logs you can get the following information about transactions :
- Allocated Heap
- Number of SOQL queries
- Number of query rows
- Number of SOSL queries
- Number of DML statements
- Number of DML rows
- Maximum CPU time
- Maximum heap size
- Number of callouts
- Number of Email Invocations
- Number of future calls
- Number of queueable jobs added to the queue
- Number of Mobile Apex push calls
    
You can manage the details of information you see in the log by specifying different debug log levels. We will get there.
## How To Use?

### Add System.debug to your code (optional)

You can track standard system debug logs, or you can add your own. To track your debug logs the only thing you need to do is add `System.debug` statement into your code.
### Set a new trace flag

The next step is to set a **new trace flag**.

**![](https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXfURmA3Q1wrFsMQp53JvHfQNy3LLiiAJLLuYGl5bU4PgexfUW1swNcBORySDb28-VZ8beoEOdcU_oPq2y7HYlOGjTO74fBCgZhJMt_sNWx6sU5l-juV1EPJzxSyHB4OqugiqBZqyg?key=g3kw6mfKlBRAQPyIVZ4_UWO4)

1. Navigate to **Setup** > **Debug Logs**.
2. Click **New** to add user trace flags.
3. Chose Tracked Entity Type, Tracked Entity Name, etc. Check steps below.
#### Choose Tracked Entity Type

**Tracked Entity Type**

Possible Tracked Entity Types are:
- Automated Process
- Platform Integration
- User
- Apex Class
- Apex Trigger

The most common approach is to use the **User** entity type and try to replicate the issue as a user. If you are the one who is going to replicate the issue, choose yourself. If someone else is going to do it, choose that person.
#### Choose Tracked Entity Name

**Tracked Entity Name**

Here, you can choose what exactly you want to track. Values in that list are dependent on the Tracked Entity Type mentioned above.

| Tracked Entity Type  | Tracked Entity Name                       |
| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| Automated Process    | Automated Process (Always)                |
| Platform Integration | Platform Integration User (Always)        |
| User                 | Choose the user you want to track         |
| Apex Class           | Choose the apex class you want to track   |
| Apex Trigger         | Choose the apex trigger you want to track |
#### Choose Start and Expiration Date

**Start Date and Expiration Date**

Select a period that will be enough to debug your code. I recommend to leave default 30 minutes. **Do not select long periods** because your entity will be tracked the whole time, generating an enormous number of logs that will block the [generation of new logs](#too-many-logs) for other developers.
#### Choose Debug Level

**Debug Level**

As we can read in [the documentation](#bookmark=id.jmkb2fhnolv8):

_To specify the level of information that gets included in debug logs, set up trace flags and debug levels. The debug levels assigned to your trace flags **control the type and amount of information that is logged for different events**. ~ Salesforce_

Long story short, the debug log level controls the amount of information you are going to see in your logs. Usually, we use a predefined level such as **SFDC_DevConsole**. If you need more information, create a New Debug Level as described below.
##### New Debug Level

When default debug levels are not enough, you can create your own debug level. Before you do that, you need to understand **Category**, **Level,** and **Event Types.**

![](data:image/png;base64,)
###### Categories

There is nothing you can do about categories. You can just configure **Levels** and see which **Event Types** will be logged for each category. If you debugging Apex Code, focus on **Apex Code** category, other categories levels set to NONE, ERROR, WARN, INFO or DEBUG, to not log to many information if you are not interested.

|Category|Description|
|---|---|
|Database|Includes information about database activity, including every data manipulation language (DML) statement or inline SOQL or SOSL query.|
|Workflow|Includes information for workflow rules, flows, and processes, such as the rule name and the actions taken.|
|NBA|Includes information about Einstein Next Best Action activity, including strategy execution details from Strategy Builder.|
|Validation|Includes information about validation rules, such as the name of the rule and whether the rule evaluated true or false.|
|Callout|Includes the request-response XML that the server is sending and receiving from an external web service. Useful when debugging issues related to using Lightning Platform web service API calls or troubleshooting user access to external objects via Salesforce Connect.|
|Apex Code|Includes information about Apex code. Can include information such as log messages generated by DML statements, inline SOQL or SOSL queries, the start and completion of any triggers, and the start and completion of any test method.|
|Apex Profiling|Includes cumulative profiling information, such as the limits for your namespace and the number of emails sent.|
|Visualforce|Includes information about Visualforce events, including serialization and deserialization of the view state or the evaluation of a formula field in a Visualforce page.|
|System|Includes information about calls to all system methods such as the System.debug method.|
###### Levels

The levels are listed from lowest to highest.
- NONE
- ERROR
- WARN
- INFO
- DEBUG
- FINE
- FINER
- FINEST

Each level specify how many information is going to appear in your logs, to be more presise, highest the level - more event types for specific category is going to be logged. Try to avoid using **FINE**, **FINER** and **FINEST** when it's not needed. It's going to create an enormus amount of logs.
###### Event Types

The combination of log category and log level specifies which events get logged. 
Event Types will be automatically updated based on the Level you specify.

For instance:

|Category|Level|Events|
|---|---|---|
|Database|**None**|-|
|Database|**Warn**|FOR_UPDATE_LOCKS_RELEASE;|
|Database|**Info**|SOQL_EXECUTE_BEGIN; SOQL_EXECUTE_END; SOSL_EXECUTE_BEGIN; SOSL_EXECUTE_END; QUERY_MORE_ITERATIONS; DML_BEGIN; DML_END; FOR_UPDATE_LOCKS_RELEASE; BULK_DML_RETRY; SAVEPOINT_SET; SAVEPOINT_ROLLBACK; SAVEPOINT_RESET; SAVEPOINT_RELEASE;|
|Database|**Fine**|SOQL_EXECUTE_BEGIN; SOQL_EXECUTE_END; SOSL_EXECUTE_BEGIN; SOSL_EXECUTE_END; QUERY_MORE_ITERATIONS; DML_BEGIN; DML_END; FOR_UPDATE_LOCKS_RELEASE; USER_MODE_PERMSET_APPLIED; BULK_DML_RETRY; SAVEPOINT_SET; SAVEPOINT_ROLLBACK; SAVEPOINT_RESET; SAVEPOINT_RELEASE;|
|Database|**Finest**|SOQL_EXECUTE_BEGIN; SOQL_EXECUTE_END; SOQL_EXECUTE_EXPLAIN; SOSL_EXECUTE_BEGIN; SOSL_EXECUTE_END; QUERY_MORE_ITERATIONS; QUERY_MORE_BEGIN; QUERY_MORE_END; DML_BEGIN; DML_END; FOR_UPDATE_LOCKS_RELEASE; IDEAS_QUERY_EXECUTE; USER_MODE_PERMSET_APPLIED; BULK_DML_RETRY; SAVEPOINT_SET; SAVEPOINT_ROLLBACK; SAVEPOINT_RESET; SAVEPOINT_RELEASE;|

Once again: Try to avoid choosing **FINE**, **FINER** and **FINEST** , that level will create an enormous amount of logs, which can lead to [too many logs](#too-many-logs) issues.
## Debug Logs in Action

Debug logs contains timestamp and event identifier:

![[Pasted image 20250428100411.png]]

- **timestamp**: Consists of the time when the event occurred and a value between parentheses. The time is in the users time zone and in the formatHH:mm:ss.SSS. The value in parentheses represents the time elapsed in nanoseconds since the start of the request. T
- **event identifier**: Specifies the event that triggered the debug log entry (such as`SAVEPOINT_RESET`or`VALIDATION_RULE`).

## Where To Use?

### Debug code on Sandbox

You can easily debug every environment, where you can easily add `System.debug` statements. When you add `System.debug` in your code you can deploy them to your org. Then set the trace flag on your user and see what happened in your code. 
### Debug code on Production

Salesforce requires at least 75% code coverage across Apex classes and triggers to deploy to production. Usually deploying code to prod, requires approvals and going through whole CICD process. Don't get me wrong, that's good. Otherwise we would end up in chaos. However it's not good for `System.debug`, because of reasons I've mentioned it's hard to add `System.debug` directly in production code to debug it. 
However, debug logs can still be useful to check if some unhandled exceptions were thrown. What you have to do is to add a new trace flags on your user or process and replicate the issue. After that check **Debug Logs** section and the **Status** columns to see if there are any unexpected problems.

## Common Issues

### System.debug leftovers

`System.debug` can drastically influence Apex performance. If you have a lot of `System.debug` statements - especially inside loops or frequently called methods they can **increase CPU time**

```java
for (Account account : accounts) {
    System.debug(account);  // Called 10,000 times in a loop!
}
```

Unlike some languages, where debug statements are stripped from code in production, Apex does not do this. That means that `System.debug` will use CPU time, because the paramenters are serialized every time. Every debug statement you leave in your code will increase the CPU usage of your code. Conceptually, heavy use of debugging can lead to CPU timeout errors.

Another reason not to leave debug statements in production code is that they can include sensitive information. We usually can easily download and share those logs with other developers, what can lead to sensitive information leak.

You may think: "yeah, maybe performance will be a little bit worst, but I will save time during debugging". Oh, yes, and know. First of all you cannot be sure that `System.debug` statements that left will log exactly information that you need. Second, to log information good developers use logging frameworks like [Nebula Logger](https://github.com/jongpie/NebulaLogger) , not debug logs. Third, there are other ways to debug your code, not only debug statements.
### Truncated Strings

#### Problem

As we can read in [the documentation:](#bookmark=id.v5u7bz9635ow)

_To help prevent connection pool timeouts caused by exceptionally large queries, strings are now truncated at **512 characters** in the Developer Consoles Log Inspector. ~ Salesforce_

Strings are truncated to prevent a performance decrease due to large logs. However, sometimes we need to preview the whole value (e.g., a JSON response from an external system).
#### Solution 1

Solution 1: [Download the raw log file](#bookmark=id.wbr00gvn4not).

1. Open **Developer Console.**
2. Select the **Logs tab** at the bottom.
3. Right-click a log and select **Open Raw Log**.
#### Solution 2

Solution 2: Use JSON.serializePretty.

Instead of `System.debug(value);` use `_System.debug(JSON.serializePretty(value));` `JSON.serializePretty` can be externally useful when it comes to display values from SObject, Maps, Sets, List, or Apex Wrappers.

**Note!** Logs like that can be of a big size, so use them only when needed and never leave them in production code.

`System.debug(value);`

![](data:image/png;base64,)

`System.debug(JSON.serializePretty(value));`

### Too many logs

#### Problem

As we can read in [the documentation](#bookmark=id.esqgn073mlql):

_When your org accumulates more than 1,000 MB of debug logs, we prevent users in the org from adding or editing trace flags. To add or edit trace flags so that you can generate more logs after you reach the limit, delete some debug logs. [1] ~ Salesforce_

You will see that error: _Cannot add or update trace flag. Debug logs storage limit exceeded. Delete some logs to free space._

You have to remove debug logs. There are a few ways to do this:
#### Solution 1

Through Debug Logs UI:

1. **Setup** > **Debug Logs** > Click the **Delete All** button.
#### Solution 2

Through [Developer Consoles Query Editor](#bookmark=id.9oirqzcktvcb):

2. Open Developer Console.
3. At the bottom of the console, select the **Query Editor** tab.
4. Select **Use Tooling API**.
5. Enter this SOQL query: _SELECT Id, StartTime, LogUserId, LogLength, Location FROM ApexLog_
6. Click **Execute**.
7. Select the logs you want to delete.
8. Click **Delete Row.**
9. To confirm the log deletion, click **Yes**.
    
![](data:image/png;base64,)

Sometimes, when you select too many logs at once and try to remove it there can be an issue. Try to select around 50-100 logs and remove them at once.
